# Execution Rules

Default verification commands:

- `./gradlew test`
- `./gradlew build`

MUST:

- Prefer the Gradle wrapper over system Gradle.
- Choose the narrowest verification command that proves the change.
- Report any command you could not run and why.
- Check `docs/STATUS.md` for active checkpoints before Docker, database, or end-to-end validation.
- Follow any verification scope defined in the active plan or relevant backlog.
- Use `docs/backlog/PHASE{n}.md` for product verification scope and `docs/backlog/HARNESS.md` for harness verification scope.
- Treat failed verification as `FAIL -> RECOVER -> PLAN`; do not proceed to checkpoint until the failure is reported and resolved or explicitly accepted.

NEVER:

- Run destructive commands.
- Run privileged commands.
- Use alternate build tools unless the repository explicitly requires them.

Allowed checkpoint commands ONLY when required by active work verification:

- `docker compose ...`
- `psql ...`

## CI Trigger Structure (DR-009)

- `develop` branch push: Checkstyle lint only
- `PR to main`: Full test suite

## Code Quality Commands

- `./gradlew checkstyleMain` — main sources lint
- `./gradlew checkstyleTest` — test sources lint
- `./gradlew check` — lint + test combined

## Makefile Shortcuts

- `make run` — Docker Compose full stack (`-p base-msa-template`)
- `make build` — Gradle full build
- `make test` — full test suite
- `make logs` — Docker Compose logs
- `make ps` — running container status
